1)A command to delete a directory with files in it is :

┌──(raakin㉿DESKTOP-0FFMSPJ)-[~]
└─$ rm -rf [example directory]

2)zip and unzip:
zip:
raakin@DESKTOP-0FFMSPJ:~$ zip -r output.zip  f1.txt f2.txt
unzip:
raakin@DESKTOP-0FFMSPJ:~$ unzip output.zip
Archive:  output.zip
replace f1.txt? [y]es, [n]o, [A]ll, [N]one, [r]ename: y
 extracting: f1.txt
replace f2.txt? [y]es, [n]o, [A]ll, [N]one, [r]ename: y
 extracting: f2.txt
============================================================================
df:
The df command checks your Linux system’s disk usage,
displaying the used space in percentage and kilobyte (KB).
The syntax looks like this:
raakin@DESKTOP-0FFMSPJ:~$ df
Filesystem      1K-blocks      Used Available Use% Mounted on
none              4015208         0   4015208   0% /usr/lib/modules/6.6.87.2-microsoft-standard-WSL2
none              4015208         4   4015204   1% /mnt/wsl
drivers         248962044 236309164  12652880  95% /usr/lib/wsl/drivers
/dev/sdd       1055762868   3064120 998995276   1% /
none              4015208        76   4015132   1% /mnt/wslg
none              4015208         0   4015208   0% /usr/lib/wsl/lib
rootfs            4010192      2672   4007520   1% /init
none              4015208       804   4014404   1% /run
none              4015208         0   4015208   0% /run/lock
none              4015208         0   4015208   0% /run/shm
none              4015208        76   4015132   1% /mnt/wslg/versions.txt
none              4015208        76   4015132   1% /mnt/wslg/doc
C:\             248962044 236309164  12652880  95% /mnt/c
D:\             975293872 340561760 634732112  35% /mnt/d
snapfuse            75776     75776         0 100% /snap/core22/2139
snapfuse            75776     75776         0 100% /snap/core22/2133
snapfuse            52224     52224         0 100% /snap/snapd/25577
snapfuse            52096     52096         0 100% /snap/snapd/25202
snapfuse             4608      4608         0 100% /snap/tree/54
tmpfs              803040        20    803020   1% /run/user/1000
